More Communication Does Not Result in Smaller Generalization Error in Federated Learning

Abstract

We study the generalization error of statistical learning models in a Federated Learning (FL) setting. Specifically, there are Kğ¾K devices or clients, each holding an independent own dataset of size nğ‘›n. Individual models, learned locally via Stochastic Gradient Descent, are aggregated (averaged) by a central server into a global model and then sent back to the devices. We consider multiple (say Râˆˆâ„•âˆ—ğ‘…superscriptâ„•R\in\mathbb{N}^{*}) rounds of model aggregation and study the effect of Rğ‘…R on the generalization error of the final aggregated model. We establish an upper bound on the generalization error that accounts explicitly for the effect of Rğ‘…R (in addition to the number of participating devices Kğ¾K and dataset size nğ‘›n). It is observed that, for fixed (n,K)ğ‘›ğ¾(n,K), the bound increases with Rğ‘…R, suggesting that the generalization of such learning algorithms is negatively affected by more frequent communication with the parameter server. Combined with the fact that the empirical risk, however, generally decreases for larger values of Rğ‘…R, this indicates that Rğ‘…R might be a parameter to optimize to reduce the population risk of FL algorithms. The results of this paper, which extend straightforwardly to the heterogeneous data setting, are also illustrated through numerical examples.

I-A Main Contributions

As we already mentioned, in this paper we study the expected generalization error as defined byÂ (6). We focus on the case in which the loss function â„“â€‹(â‹…,â‹…)â„“â‹…â‹…\ell(\cdot,\cdot) can be expressed as a Bregman divergenceÂ [9]. This encompasses a large family of loss functions, including the squared Euclidean distance commonly used in regression problems. We establish an upper bound on the generalization errorÂ (6) that accounts explicitly for the number of rounds Rğ‘…R. Essentially, the proof techniques involve bounding steps that account judiciously for the statistical correlations induced byÂ (2) and which build up through the rounds. Furthermore, by studying its evolution with the number of rounds Rğ‘…R we observe that, for fixed (n,K)ğ‘›ğ¾(n,K), the established bound can increase with Rğ‘…R, suggesting that the generalization of FL-SGD is negatively affected by more frequent communication with the parameter server. Combined with known results about that the empirical risk, however, generally decreases for larger values of Rğ‘…R, this indicates that Rğ‘…R might be a parameter to optimize in order to reduce the population risk of FL-SGD algorithms. These results, which for simplicity are established here for the i.i.d. data setting and extend easily to the heterogeneous (non i.i.d.) setting, are also illustrated through some numerical examples in which the bound is compared to the true (measured) generalization error.

It is noteworthy that the results of this paper extend easily to the case of aperiodic communication with the parameter server and/or more general aggregated models WÂ¯(r)superscriptÂ¯ğ‘Šğ‘Ÿ\overline{W}^{(r)}, such as any arbitrary deterministic function of the local models {Wk(r,Ï„)}k=1Ksuperscriptsubscriptsuperscriptsubscriptğ‘Šğ‘˜ğ‘Ÿğœğ‘˜1ğ¾\{W_{k}^{(r,\tau)}\}_{k=1}^{K} among which the arithmetic averageÂ (1) that we consider here is a common choiceÂ [10]. Finally, the analysis also carries over easily for settings in which local model updates also account for additional stochasticity through added noise in the gradient steps, i.e., whenÂ (3) is substituted by the more general

I-B Related Works

A major focus of machine learning research over recent years has been the study of statistical learning algorithms when applied to data generated and processed in a distributed (network or graph) mannerÂ [10, 11, 12]. Such setups are of prime importance, especially when some degree of privacy is requiredÂ [13, 14, 15, 16] and/or computational power is limitedÂ [17, 16]. The study of the behavior of the generalization error, a problem which is understood only very partially even in centralized learning settings, is even more challenging in the case of distributed and multi-round algorithms such as the popular FLÂ [10]. In particular, while a few worksÂ [1, 2] have already demonstrated that multi-round communication generally yields smaller empirical risk, only very little is known about the effect of the number of communication rounds on the generalization error. For the special case of one-round communication, sometimes referred to as â€œdistributed learning" or â€œone-shot" FL, bounds on the generalization error that improve upon the corresponding ones for the centralized setting with, essentially a factor of 1/K1ğ¾1/\sqrt{K}, are established inÂ [8] for linear and location models and losses that can be expressed as Bregman divergence; and inÂ [6] andÂ [5] for a broader class of loss functions, using information-theoretic and rate-distortion theoretic approaches.

Compared with the multi-round setup that we study here, the one-round setup suffers from the lack of a joint optimization guarantee, i.e., it may not be possible to make the empirical risk arbitrarily small. From a theoretical angle, however, the study of the generalization error in this latter case is less difficult comparatively, as there are no statistical couplings among the devicesâ€™ models by the memoryless assumption on the dataset. Most relevant to the problem that we study in this paper is the recent workÂ [8]. InÂ [8], the authors study a quantity, which they argue as being a proxy to the true generalization error as defined byÂ (6), given as

Appendix B Details of the experiments

Datasets

We conducted the simulations on datasets implemented in the open source Machine Learning library Scikit-Learn [24], which are â€œcalifornia_housing" and â€œfriedman1". The results of our numerical experiments were consistent with both datasets; Figure 3 presents simulations using â€œfriedman1" dataset.

Model & algorithm implementation

OLS and LocalSGD are implemented using SGDRegressor from Scikit-Learn and custom Python classes.

Training and hyperparameters

The models were trained for one epoch, to coincide with the theoretical setup of this paper. The learning rate was set to Î·=0.01ğœ‚0.01\eta=0.01.

Hardware and other resources

We performed our experiments on a machine equipped with 56 CPUs Intel Xeon E5-2690v4 2.60GHz. The experiments are conducted using Python language.
